  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What does the \"@\" symbol mean in Objective-C?",
  "response": "In Objective-C, the \"@\" symbol is used as a prefix for various language constructs and directives. Here are some common uses of the \"@\" symbol in Objective-C:\n\n1. **String Literals**:  \n   The \"@\" symbol is used to create an `NSString` object from a C-style string.  \n   Example:  \n   ```objective-c\n   NSString *myString = @\"Hello, World!\";\n   ```\n\n2. **Class and Protocol Declarations**:  \n   The \"@\" symbol is used in declarations for classes, protocols, and categories.  \n   Example:  \n   ```objective-c\n   @interface MyClass : NSObject\n   @end\n   @protocol MyProtocol\n   @end\n   @interface MyClass (MyCategory)\n   @end\n   ```\n\n3. **Property Declarations**:  \n   The \"@\" symbol is used to declare properties in a class.  \n   Example:  \n   ```objective-c\n   @property (nonatomic, strong) NSString *name;\n   ```\n\n4. **Synthesize Statements**:  \n   The \"@\" symbol is used in `@synthesize` to automatically generate getter and setter methods for properties.  \n   Example:  \n   ```objective-c\n   @synthesize name = _name;\n   ```\n\n5. **Dynamic Properties**:  \n   The \"@\" symbol is used with `@dynamic` to indicate that the getter and setter methods will be provided at runtime.  \n   Example:  \n   ```objective-c\n   @dynamic name;\n   ```\n\n6. **Compiler Directives**:  \n   The \"@\" symbol is used in compiler directives such as `@autoreleasepool`, `@try`, `@catch`, `@finally`, and `@throw` for exception handling and memory management.  \n   Example:  \n   ```objective-c\n   @autoreleasepool {\n       // Code that uses autorelease\n   }\n   @try {\n       // Code that might throw an exception\n   } @catch (NSException *exception) {\n       // Exception handling\n   } @finally {\n       // Code that always executes\n   }\n   ```\n\n7. **Selector and Protocol References**:  \n   The \"@\" symbol is used to refer to selectors and protocols.  \n   Example:  \n   ```objective-c\n   SEL mySelector = @selector(myMethod);\n   id<MyProtocol> object;\n   ```\n\n8. **Boxed Expressions**:  \n   The \"@\" symbol is used for boxed expressions to convert primitive values into objects.  \n   Example:  \n   ```objective-c\n   NSNumber *number = @(42);\n   NSValue *rectValue = @(CGRectMake(0, 0, 100, 100));\n   ```\n\n9. **Dictionary and Array Literals**:  \n   The \"@\" symbol is used for creating `NSDictionary` and `NSArray` literals.  \n   Example:  \n   ```objective-c\n   NSArray *array = @[@\"one\", @\"two\", @\"three\"];\n   NSDictionary *dict = @{@\"key\": @\"value\"};\n   ```\n\nIn summary, the \"@\" symbol in Objective-C serves as a marker for many language-specific features and constructs, distinguishing them from standard C syntax.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
